62 XVII. “ But you will say that at the time when we are experiencing them the w‘sions we have in sleep have the same appearance as the visual pre- sentations that we experience while awake ἔ To begin with, there is a difference between them ; but do not let us dwell on that, for our point is that when we are asleep we have not the same mental or sensory power and fulness of function as we have when awake. Even men acting under the influence of wine do not act with the same decision as they do when sober: they are doubtful and hesitating and sometimes pull themselves up, and they give a more feeble assent to their sense-presentations and, when they have slept it off, realize how unsubstantial those presentations were.
